He de- dicated his treatise “ De mysteriis rerum que sunt in ecelesia,⁷’ of which a notice will be found hereafter‚ to F ulke Basset, Bishop of London 1241- 1259. Mr. Wright has entered more sully into the history of John de Garlandia in the Introduction to his poem De triumphis Ecclesia editcd for the Roxburghe Club‚ and also in an introductory note in the edition of the Dictionarz'us above mentioned.³ He expresses the conclusion, to which I had been likewise led to incline, that these treatises should be assigned to the early part of the thirteenth century.

The author of the Promptorium has drawn so largely upon these obscure relies of mediaeval learning that the vexed questions connected with John de Garlandia‚ and the precise period when he wrote these grammatical treatises once so highly esteemed, are not devoid of interest. Upon this point of literary history, however, the evidence has been conclusively summed up by the Rev. J. E. E. Mayor in a dissertation in the Journal of Philology which I have already cited.b Mr. Mayor observes that “the patriotic attempt of Dom Rivet (Hist. Litt. de la F rance, viii. 83) to esta- blish the French descent of J ohannes de Garlandia has been defeated by the fairness of a later editor of that noble work, M. Victor le Clerc (ibid. xxi. 369), who has also proved that Johannes lived, not in the eleventh century, as Geraud maintained as late as 1837, but amid the intellectual stir of the thirteenth.
